	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>I'm sorry, but my principles made me beat the shit out of you</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>I am a firm believer in the policy that violence, in this day and age, doesn't solve anything.  While it may be a great solution for short term goals, it often has long term consequences.<br />
<br />
Forestory.  I've recently taken a job at a supermarket deli.  Because I pretty much already know everything that needs to be done there (it's the simplest food operation I've ever worked at), I'm in the position of being a shift manager in all but name and pay, which comes at my 6 months.  Yay.  This places me in an awkward position.  My manager places me in charge of everyone else there, people who have all been there much longer than I have.  While seniority has nothing to do with ability/authority, this has caused resentment amongst a few people.<br />
<br />
Like this little Armenian kid.  Let's just call him Jay.  Jay has a crush on this girl, who, just because, we'll call Emily.  Emily does not approve of Jay's advances, which often turn physical.<br />
<br />
I am placed further in the awkward position of having everyone in the supermarket think I'm seeing this girl.  That's only a half-truth, but we'll get back to why this is relevant at all later.<br />
<br />
A couple of weeks ago, Jay gives this girl a good squeeze from behind, and she turns around and yells &quot;Stop touching me!&quot;  I kinda like Jay.  He's a bit of a dork, and he does some fucking stupid things kitchen wise (he's almost stabbed me in the thigh 3 times now, which led to a <i>long</i> heart to heart on knife saftey), but he's kind of a cute little mascot.  This was not the first time I'd seen him do something like this, but it's the first time I'd seen Emily get so pissed off about it.  It happens again a couple hours later, and I pull Jay aside.<br />
<br />
&quot;Jay, you have to understand that Emily's not too happy about you touching her.  You have to knock that shit off, or you're going to get in trouble.  What if she decides to file sexual harrassment charges on you?&quot;<br />
&quot;Oh, I'm sorry man, no problem, don't worry about it.&quot; <b>Strike One.</b><br />
<br />
We now jump to Christmas Eve, a day which was pure hell in terms of the quantity and quality of customers.  Everyone was an asshole, putting me in a fairly lousy disposition.  I'm <i>incredible</i> at presenting a sunshiny face and pleasant attitude to a customer no matter my disposition.  I have the ability to eat shit and grin so long as I'm getting paid for it.  However, this means I tend to get pissed off at the people who I <i>can</i> get pissed off at- namely, my fellow employees.  I could have gotten pissed off at the comicly stereotypical lazy Puerto Rican, but I knew he was getting fired after Christmas, so I wasn't in a big hurry.  I could have gotten pissed at Emily, as she is sometimes slow to think, which when hands must move fast is a Very Bad Thing, but dear God, she has the <i>greatest</i> ass, and I just can't stay mad when she turns around.  Which leaves Jay, who gave me my excuse when he gives her stomach a good squeeze, and she responds by spinning around and shoving him.  I once again direct him to a back room.<br />
<br />
&quot;Jay, I warned you about this before, and now I'm dead fucking serious.  Three things will happen- either you will stop touching Emily, because she is not attracted to you and is really upset with you touching her; second, she's going to go to the big boss and get you fired; or third, she <i>won't</i> go to the big boss to get you fired, and then I'll have to defend my principles and beat the shit out of you.  I don't hold well with the shit you're pulling.&quot;<br />
&quot;Jay, I like you, and I really, really don't want to have to beat the crap out of you.  But if you keep this up, I'm not going to be left with a choice.&quot;<b>Strike Two.</b><br />
<br />
I get the whole &quot;no problem&quot; speech.  Seeing as he thinks I'm being both a) overassertive of my quasi-authority and b) jealous and defensive, he pretty much ignores me.  Neither of these things are true.  I really wish I wasn't in the position of being in charge, or having the wrong people see us leave to hang out after work.  This is unnecessary complication here.  I wish things could be very straightforward.<br />
<br />
See, here's my whole moral take on the whole situation.  I'm willing to let Emily handle it- to a point.  I've talked to her about it, and she's never explicitly told me to talk to Jay, but let the point sink in that she'd appreciate it if I did.  However, there comes a point where I feel I have to settle things myself.  Jay does not care if he gets fired.  Fortunately, neither do I; in fact, the guarantee I have of the shift manager position (with pay) comes from my boss knowing I have no problems leaving if I don't get it as soon as I'm eligible.  I don't need the job desperately; it's merely supplemental to my other job.<br />
<br />
I knew right then I was going to have to beat the shit out of him.  It wasn't a question of whether I was capable; I've got a thin, light, wiry frame, but he is a wimp and I am trained.  That's specificly why I don't like fighting, because I know what the hell I'm doing and there are better ways to solve things.  Get your kids involved in karate or wrestling, an envirornment where they can learn these kinds of lessons (of course, research your coach- my first wrestling coach was caught fleeing on foot from police officers after a DUI pullover- while he was running for town council, humorously enough.)  I knew that even if I asked her to, she wouldn't go to the big boss.  And I knew that while if I beat the crap out of him, she'd be upset (she doesn't really hate him that much, except for the touching bullshti), if I filed charges for her, she'd fucking kill me.  If you don't get it, don't question it.<br />
<br />
No matter how many times I thought it over, I realized that the absolute best possible way to solve this situation was to beat the shit out of this poor kid.<br />
<br />
Which happened tonight.  The three of us are on again, and sure enough, he grabs that beautiful ass of hers.  Dear sweet lord, I <i>love</i> that ass.  I do not say anything.  Judgement has been rendered, sentence has been passed, and need for further commentary is worthless.  There are no appeals in Claud Court.  A judge need not enjoy the execution of his sentence.<b>Strike Three.</b><br />
<br />
Before Emily leaves at the end of her shift, I tell her about my decision for Jay.  Naturally, she's pissed that I've taken this kind of liberty, but I tell her my mind's made up and that she can go talk to the big boss or go home.<br />
<br />
She looks me straight in the eyes and tells me she's just going to grab her coat and go home.  Don't bother calling me.  Yay.  [b]Real World: 1  Fighting for Principles: 0[b]<br />
<br />
I close with Jay, and as he's getting ready to leave, I tell him to wait up.  He played it off well, but he jumped just a little bit.<br />
<br />
&quot;Jay, do you remember what I told you last time?&quot;<br />
&quot;Oh no, man, what are you talking about?&quot; Every word a blatant lie.<br />
&quot;What did I tell you would happen if you kept touching Emily?&quot;<br />
<br />
I never saw recognition come across his face.  He knew as soon as I held him up what was going on.  What I saw was a look of <i>realization</i>; Jay discovered that I had been very, very, very serious the last time, in a way that my eyes bulging from my sockets and my loudest &quot;don't let the customers hear you cussing someone out&quot; voice couldn't convey.<br />
<br />
&quot;I thought you were joking around!!&quot;<br />
&quot;I wasn't, and she doesn't want to file sexual harrassment charges.  So we're going to go to the back lot where the cameras don't cover, and I'm going to beat the shit out of you.&quot;<br />
<br />
He proceeds to tell me that I can't make him come out with me, and that I can't make him fight me.  I cannot dispute this point.  However, I had already planned for this contingency, and presented him a list of alternatives.  An asskicking was inevitable, and by doing it this way I was giving him the kindness of a fair fight, something I personally felt he didn't deserve.  I could choose to jump him when he gets out of work one night, and if I did it that way, he'd never get a chance.<br />
<br />
He could not dispute <i>that</i> point.<br />
<br />
&quot;Jay, I have to reinforce with you that I <i>really</i> don't want to do this.  However, I've got some strong principles that leave me with absolutely no other choice.  This has nothing to do with Emily- if it was any other girl and I could do something about it, I'd react in the same way.&quot;<br />
<br />
Realization turned into resignation, and we punch out and trudge into the snow, and around to the back parking lot.  I have to give him credit in the fact that he didn't try to surprise me on the way out; he didn't try to slip behind me and jump me; he walked side by side with me until we got back there.  Perhaps he really understood how little I wanted to hurt him.  I really, really hope he did.  I face him and ask him if he's ready, and he puts his fists up.  I go into a wrestler's crouch because of this.<br />
<br />
I'll give him credit on another front too- he didn't stand there and wait for me to beat the crap out of him.  I expected to have to start in on him, but he came right after me.<br />
<br />
Unfortunately for him, he did it in that classic &quot;I don't know shit about fighting&quot; move, the right cross to the head.  To a wrestler, this is a great gift.  I grabbed his arm and his knee, rolled him over my back and placed him onto his.  It was over very fast from there.  I kneed him in the stomach on my way to cover him, then hit him three times in the side of the face.  Hard.  Much, much harder than I had initially intended, but enough to teach the lesson.  I got off of him and let him get to his feet.<br />
<br />
I don't know if he harbors resentment; in fact, I really don't care much about his feelings right now.  I'm pretty sure both my messages got across- I don't want to hurt you, but I will if you touch Emily, and that's the important part.  A nice, big bruise was already forming on the side of his face.<br />
<br />
&quot;Jay, you can tell whoever you want about what happened here.  You know I don't care a ton about this particular job.  But understand that if you tell people that I beat the shit out of you, they're going to ask- and eventually find out- why.  And I am far from the only person who is going to have the kind of reaction I did.&quot;<br />
<br />
He's not the kind of person who'd go to the police about this sort of thing.  His reaction would be to tell my manager what happened, and maybe he will.  We'll cross that bridge when we get to it.<br />
<br />
I am burdened with a moral conscience.  As much as I try to strip it away, shit like this happens and I am forced to act upon it.  Weak.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
