	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Fatwiz</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Would you have been so quick to &quot;teach him a lesson&quot; if he had been my size? I think it would have been more chivalrous if you said he was like 250, built, near six and a half feet tall trained in the finer points of grappling etc.  , but you were going to teach him a 'lesson' anyways, even if it meant getting your own ass whooped! </div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
Perhaps it might have.  However, that would place me in the position of being unable to solve this problem.  If I can solve it, I will.<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Fatwiz</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
doesn't conjure thoughts of duty and honor. Your primary goal was to modify his behavior, you didn't need to strike him hard in the face three times to accomplish this. If you are &quot;trained&quot; in even the basics of wrestling you could have placed him into a painful submission hold while reiterating the fact that its not nice to touch people sexually when they have asked you not to.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
You sir, do not know shit about wrestling.  First and foremost, there is no such thing as a &quot;submission hold&quot;.  That's from professional wrestling.  There is no form of wrestling you will ever be taught which teaches you &quot;submission holds.&quot;  Second, as the object of wrestling is to throw your opponent to his back and pin him to the ground, there are very few realistic (snicker) &quot;submission holds&quot; you learn, and virtually none from a standing position.  These painful &quot;submission holds&quot; are almost always applied from the position where someone is on his stomach with you above him.  The object of those holds is to create pain where the escape from pain is to roll over onto your back (guillotine, grapevine, double-leg splitter).  Moves like the guillotine and grapevine require your opponent to make a very specific mistake in order for you to gain control of a particular body part.  Moves like the double-leg splitter require your opponent to react in a specific fashion to allow you the opportunity to use it as a counter measure.<br />
<br />
You could always apply pressure on pressure points though!  And nothing modifies behavior like having the inside of your wrist or shoulder hurt for a few minutes!<br />
<br />
So Fatwiz, if you are going to lecture me on how I should be using my 4 years of wrestling, make sure you have a fucking clue what you're talking about before you let stupid shit fall out of your mouth.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
